No, no, that would dry, and tell you to keep combing it, and he'd see that it was dry before you went to bed, before he went either. Because the little boy next door you know - he was seventeen then, and - my father used to t
ell he would sit on the wall, they had a shed there and they used to bath him - in the shed, and my father's tell him, Ben, go in by the fire and in until your hair is dry, he said. Because he said, the pores all go back then, and they close. Well now the
n
 - Ben wasn't taking much notice and he was - sixteen he was, going in seventeen - and he had the typhoid fever. And it turned to gallop consumption. They were burying him at seventeen and a half. And my father used to tell my mother, you see why? My moth
er said - my father said to my mother, you are not of us to do that, he said. No. And then my mother used to make you know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15100470\charrsid12156020 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10514204\charrsid12156020  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15100470\charrsid12156020 senna }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10514204\charrsid12156020 tea for us then you know, and we had to have it on the Friday then because - on the weekend you see. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11172311 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10514204\charrsid12156020 Did you have to have it every Friday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1400613 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10514204\charrsid12156020 
MM? Every Fri - every weekend. Yes. And then she'd buy worm lozenges. Oh when I - and every spring - she would make brimstone and treacle - in a big big pan for then we had to - take a big spoonful and - and I had awful weak st
omach you know when I was small. I didn't eat - used to eat much. I never was more than six stone. I'm only six stone seven now. And - my mother used to turn it now and when it - my turn came I suppose - swallow it, she'd say, swallow it. And you had to s
w
allow it. Ooh then when we - and we had that for nine mornings every spring. Yes. And if we had a toothache you know, my father'd go for figs. And he'd open a fig you know, and he'd put it between your gums - and your cheek. For to break inside and not br
e
ak outside 'Cos I had a friend you know, and I used to tell him - what is that scar dad on that face there? He said, teeth out. Yes. And you know - he - sometimes he'd put - a basin of hot boiling water, and put something over your head and open your mout
h
 you know, for to inhale - that steam you know, to break the gathering. Yes. Oh my father was very careful. And my father was with my - and the doctor when my mother had - children. Yes. I notice on the paper it says now too you know - what husband for wi
l
ling to stand - when the woman - is delivering - when the - woman is having a baby. Yes. I remember my father - I remember my mother saying, that - when she had the second or the eldest daughter, she said, you have a doctor. And of course they knew the do
c
tor. Well my mother was in service I remember now, in Mangers in the Hafod, he was the manager, and he thought the world of my mother, and this Doctor Lewis was by him you know, and my mother had him now, and my father used to tell him, there you are now,
 
stop pulling. Pulling the child you know. Give a rest, he said. And I'll carry on now, he used to tell the doctor, my father used to tell the doctor that, yes. I remember when this youngest baby died, Doctor Gabriel Morriston - the old man, he used to com
e
 down to us, that - that's - we did have a doctor in Plas Mall then, well only one in Moriston, and my father said to the doctor - there's fits here doctor, he said. Oh no, no, no, no, Mr Rhys, he said, nonsense, he said. Yes, he said, there's fits in - h
ere. And - the last one I told you - went bad on that dark day. Well - oh no, he said, it'll be all right, he said. So anyhow - he said, when he was going now through the passage to the front door, my father called him back. Doctor - \{BLANK\}
 And he said, come back doctor, he said. And the doctor came back, for he was hard of hearing - from - his - his daughter's living at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Swansea{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 now. Because - she sent a letter - to my nephew, she was invited to that wedding, and my father would like this be to - he'd - he'
d make all that medicines, now what do I - going to tell you, he'd get to - oh - mallow leaves they call it, I don't know what you call them in English, there was a little purple flower on it, and used to - like an ivy leaf only softer, boil them - all go
od for gatherings you know. And he'd put a poultice on you - for him. Oh yes, my father was very watchful like that, when we was children.
